# lat.md Knowledge Graph Maintenance

## When to Update lat.md/

After completing any of these changes, update the relevant `lat.md/` page and run `lat check`:

- Created a new service, module, or domain boundary
- Renamed or moved classes/functions referenced by `[[src/]]` links
- Changed the architecture of an existing domain (new dependencies, merged services)
- Added `# @lat:` annotations to source files
- Modified more than 5 files in a single feature touching documented domains

## Quick Commands

```bash
lat check                    # Validate all links — run after every structural change
lat refs "<section-id>"      # Find code referencing a concept before modifying it
lat search "<query>"         # Semantic search (requires LAT_LLM_KEY)
lat section "<section-id>"   # Read a specific section
lat expand "<section-id>"    # Section content with inline code snippets
```

## What NOT to Update in lat.md/

- Operational knowledge (decisions, preferences, runbooks) → use `memory/`
- Session summaries → use `MEMORY.md` pointers
- Single-file edits that don't change architecture
- Test or config file changes

## Annotation Syntax

```python
# @lat: [[page-name#Section Name]]    # Python
```

```go
// @lat: [[page-name#Section Name]]   // Go, JS, TS
```

## Rules

- `[[src/]]` links must reference exact symbol names as they appear in code
- Every `lat.md/` section needs a leading paragraph ≤250 characters
- `lat.md/` is project-specific — never sync via `cursor-sync`
- Only the `lat-md` skill file and this rule file propagate across repos
